<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910222-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>910222-0022.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- CareerCom Corp.:   Home-Office Staff Trimmed   By 10%; Salaries Are Cut</HL><DATE>02/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   CCM</CO><IN>CONSUMER andamp; HOUSEHOLD SERVICES, LAWN CARE, TAX PREPARATION (CSV)</IN><LP>   CareerCom Corp., in an effort to counter the effect ofdeclining revenue, said it has laid off 10% of itshome-office staff and reduced salaries, among othercost-cutting measures.   The layoffs affected about 13 employees at the operator ofcareer training schools. CareerCom's president and chiefexecutive officer, Robert A. Smith, said the company was alsoseeking to shed unprofitable schools. The Middletown, Pa.,company currently operates 67 career training institutions inNorth America.</LP><TEXT>   The actions come after several months of decliningrevenues. For the fiscal year ended Sept. 30, 1990, CareerComreported revenue of $138 million, down from $145.5 million in1990. For the first quarter of fiscal 1991, ended Dec. 31,1990, CareerCom said revenue fell to $35.5 million, from$40.4 million a year earlier. Mr. Smith cited decliningenrollments in the company's trucking schools as one reasonfor the decline.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,CareerCom stock closed unchanged at $2.25.</TEXT></DOC>